<div id="review_3895694206" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3895694206" />
    <a title="James T" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/127238055-james-t"><img alt="James T" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3895694206?book_show_action=true">Mar 17, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="James T" class="user" itemprop="url" name="James T" href="/user/show/127238055-james-t">James T</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/127238055-james-t?shelf=old-favorites">old-favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3895694206" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14533341595220375105">Out of all the Tennis Shoes books, this is the one I could most see as a movie. It&apos;s very cinematic and focused.<br/><br/>The previous book left one group of time-travelers at the Tower of Babel and another in ancient America. The ancient America group makes no appearances in this book, but I think that makes the book stronger because it allows the author to focus on the Tower of Babel arc. He&apos;s able to introduce the stakes, keep a consistent flow, and have payoffs in the same book (compared to later book</span>
  <span id="freeText14533341595220375105" style="display:none">Out of all the Tennis Shoes books, this is the one I could most see as a movie. It's very cinematic and focused.<br /><br />The previous book left one group of time-travelers at the Tower of Babel and another in ancient America. The ancient America group makes no appearances in this book, but I think that makes the book stronger because it allows the author to focus on the Tower of Babel arc. He's able to introduce the stakes, keep a consistent flow, and have payoffs in the same book (compared to later books where he tried to do too many viewpoints and unrelated plots at once, so they were less focused).<br /><br />He brings in more fantastical elements, though some break continuity. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Characters being able to communicate with animals is a fun plot device but never happened in previous books, even when it would have been useful (though it gets retconned in the next book). Akish being able to travel in time seemingly at will also makes us wonder why we didn't see this before, even if we suspend our disbelief about the possibility. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />I think Heimerdinger handled the sword of Akish better in this book than in Gadiantons and the Silver Sword (book 2) where it was introduced. Book 2 had an inconsistently applied theme of using legalistic perfection to combat the corrupting influence of the sword. This book treated it more directly as a spiritual battle about the source of one's trust: prayer and faith in God, or other influences that claim to know better and to have our best interest. Which is way more relatable. And, as a good example of how this book does setup and payoffs well, characters by the end of the book have actually seen the consequences of this theme borne out. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[The bit with Joshua and Rebecca at the end is the most obvious, but Akish also realizes his defeat, and Mary for her part has an arc in this book learning to rely more on prayer. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />There was more Steffanie in this book. Her voice sometimes bordered on annoying or cringey but was fun overall. Her competitive drive and athleticism made her the perfect character for the situations she was put into. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[I'm not sure how to feel about the bit with her racing Mardon to the top of the Tower of Babel; part of the time she treats it as a pride competition, and other times she says she thinks angels are supporting her to treat Mardon a lesson. It didn't matter to the story either way, the tone just felt inconsistent. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span></span>
  <a data-text-id="14533341595220375105" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

